  "nursesNote": "The mental status examination is an objective snapshot of a patient's current mental state. The nurse assesses appearance (grooming, hygiene, dress), behavior (motor activity, eye contact), and speech (rate, volume, amount, such as pressured or poverty of speech). Mood is what the patient reports feeling, while affect is the emotion the nurse observes; the two may not match. Thought process is how thoughts flow (for example tangential or flight of ideas), and thought content includes delusions and suicidal or homicidal ideation, which the nurse assesses directly for safety. Perception covers hallucinations and illusions. Cognition includes orientation, memory, and attention. Insight is the patient's awareness of their illness, and judgment is their ability to make sound decisions. The nurse documents findings objectively and uses them to guide safety and the plan of care.",
  "providerOrders": [
    "Assess appearance, behavior, and speech",
    "Distinguish mood (reported) from affect (observed)",
    "Assess thought content for suicidal/homicidal ideation and delusions",
    "Assess perception, cognition, insight, and judgment",
    "Document findings objectively and act on safety risks"
  ],
